ce:section.ce:para:
Depending on the biological importance of derived CDs, the antibiofilm activity of CDs has been examined and explored. RCDs was veiled for their antibiofilm property against two different strains of bacteria. Aeromonas caviae and Streptococcus mutans are healthcare associated pathogens as they tend to cause illness in individuals with compromised immunity [66,67]. The bacterial strains were allowed to grow in LB medium and incubated in a shaking incubator at 37°C. An inoculum size of OD600nm∼0.01 were taken from the overnight culture and utilized in each of the experiments. Solubilized RCDs solution is taken and allowed to treat the cells at 37°C for 24h in a shaking incubator [68]. Briefly both A.caviae and S.mutans cells were incubated in a 96 well plate to form biofilms (Fig. 6
                        ). The cells were seeded along with different concentrations of RCDs (50µg/ml – 500µg/ml) and biofilm formations were monitored. RCDs have been shown to reduce the biofilm formation of A.caviae in a dose dependent manner more prominently than S.mutans (Fig. 7
                        ). This result could be possible due to the effect of RCDs on the cell wall of the gram-negative strain compared to gram-positive bacteria. The reason could be cell wall composition of gram-negative bacterium that differs from that of gram-positive bacterium. As gram positive bacteria possess a thick and composed peptidoglycan layer enriched with phosphoric acid, whereas gram-negative bacterium cell wall comprises of various layers from inside to outside ranging from thin peptides, phospholipids to lipopolysaccharides. Contingent on the variations between the composition of cell walls, RCDs have shown more reduction on A.caviae biofilms [55].
